<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Two isolates of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. verniciicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="verniciicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. verniciicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clustered in a well-supported clade (ML/BI = 100/1) and appeared closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. rostrata" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="rostrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. rostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. juglandicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="juglandicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. juglandicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogram of Diaporthe from a Maximum Likelihood analysis based on combined ITS, cal, his 3, tef 1 and tub 2. Values above the branches indicate Maximum Likelihood bootstrap (left, ML BP ≥ 50 %) and Bayesian probabilities (right, BI PP ≥ 0.90). The tree is rooted with Diaporthella corylina. Strains in current study are in blue font and the ex-type cultures are in bold font." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.77.59999.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/497460" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">1</figureCitation>
). Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. verniciicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="verniciicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. verniciicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. rostrata" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="rostrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. rostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
characterised by conidiomata with single necks erumpent through the host bark. However, the new taxon can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. rostrata" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="rostrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. rostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having smaller alpha conidia (7-8.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 vs. 8.5-11.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-015-1104-5" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 8" refId="B11" refString="Fan, XL, Hyde, KD, Udayanga, D, Wu, XY, Tian, CM, 2015. Diaporthe rostrata, a novel ascomycete from Juglans mandshurica associated with walnut dieback. Mycological Progress 14: 1 - 8, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-015-1104-5" title="Diaporthe rostrata, a novel ascomycete from Juglans mandshurica associated with walnut dieback." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-015-1104-5" volume="14" year="2015">Fan et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. verniciicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="verniciicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. verniciicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. juglandicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="juglandicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">D. juglandicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having wider alpha conidia (3-3.5 vs. 2.5-3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5943/mycosphere/8/5/3" author="Yang, Q" journalOrPublisher="Mycosphere" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" pagination="817 - 826" refId="B52" refString="Yang, Q, Fan, XL, Du, Z, Tian, CM, 2017b. Diaporthe juglandicola sp. nov. (Diaporthales, Ascomycetes), evidenced by morphological characters and phylogenetic analysis. Mycosphere 8: 817 - 826, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5943/mycosphere/8/5/3" title="Diaporthe juglandicola sp. nov. (Diaporthales, Ascomycetes), evidenced by morphological characters and phylogenetic analysis." url="https://doi.org/10.5943/mycosphere/8/5/3" volume="8" year="2017 b">Yang et al. 2017b</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first discovery of a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitschke &amp; Pyrenomyc.Germ" authorityYear="1870" class="Ascomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Diaporthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species isolated from infected branches or twigs on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lour" authorityYear="1790" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Vernicia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vernicia montana" order="Geraniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Vernicia montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and was confirmed as a new species, based on phylogeny and morphology.
</paragraph>
